TYPHOID FEVER UPDATE 2007 (07)
******************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
In this update:
[1] Marshall Islands (Majuro)
[2] Turkey (Mus)
******
[1] Marshall Islands (Majuro)
Date: Thu 15 Mar 2007
From: Brent Barrett <salbrent@sbcglobal.net>
Source: Yokwe.net [edited]


Doctors from the United States Centers for Disease Control (CDC) are
on Majuro trying to identify the source of an outbreak of typhoid
fever. According to Dr. Alex Pinano, there are currently 24 cases of
this bacterial infection in the capital atoll in the Republic of the
Marshall Islands.
The disease, most often caused by fecal contamination of the water
supply, appears to be coming from the Rita area, Dr. Pinano told
Chamber of Commerce members at the regular monthly meeting. Chamber
member, Ben Chutaro, said that problems with ground water wells were
identified in the Jenrok area, which is on the same side of the
atoll, over 2 years ago. Most households are not connected to the
island's sanitary sewers due to failure to pay for Majuro Water and
Sewer services.
Dr. Pinano said that there are vaccines for typhoid available, but
supplies are not on-island. The country does not include the vaccines
in its regime of shots. Residents should be advised to boil any
ground water obtained from wells to kill this kind of bacteria.
With the current drought in effect, there is the possibility that
some businesses may be tempted to use well water [for] the
preparation of food or what will become food, such as ice for fresh fish.
In April and May 2006, there were 22 confirmed cases [of typhoid
fever]. Local health officials voiced their concern at that time
about the increase [in the number] of typhoid cases.
[Byline: Aenet Rowa]
